3. Factor analysis

3.1. Parallel analysis: How many factors?

We assumed that there are three factors (latent or unobserved dimensions) of racial experience. Lets check this assumption. The fa.parallel function from the psyche package compares the eigenvalues of the correlation matrix (the metric of variance explained) from the observed data with the eigenvalues generated from random data. The Y-axis indicates eignevalues and the X-indicates the number of possible factors from 1 to the maximum. You can easily see that after three factors, the Y value drops immediately. I set the fm argument in the fa.parallel function to ml" (maximum likelihood estimation) to use common factor model, which assumes that covariance between items are explained by both shared latent causes as well as unexplained variable-specific variance (for more inforation, see this link). The result (a change in the slope) shows that assuming three factors is plausible to best explain the variance between items.

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  11  and the number of components =  NA

3.2. Factor analysis

After validating the nfactors = 3 assumption, I ran the factor analysis using the observed data. Please also note that I assume that these factors are orthogonal by setting the rotate = 'oblimin'.For interpretation, it means the factors show the correlations between question items and factors (for more information, see this link). The factor analysis also confirms that 3 factors are sufficient to explain the covariance between items and factors.

## 
## Factor analysis with Call: fa(r = vars, nfactors = 3, rotate = "varimax", fm = "ml")
## 
## Test of the hypothesis that 3 factors are sufficient.
## The degrees of freedom for the model is 228  and the objective function was  0.8 
## The number of observations was  6448  with Chi Square =  5153.41  with prob <  0 
## 
## The root mean square of the residuals (RMSA) is  0.03 
## The df corrected root mean square of the residuals is  0.03 
## 
## Tucker Lewis Index of factoring reliability =  0.898
## RMSEA index =  0.058  and the 10 % confidence intervals are  0.057 0.059
## BIC =  3153.5

3.3. Data visualization

Here, the goal is to visualize the relationship between each question item and three factors. I proceed in two steps. I first extract factor loadings (the correlations between items and questions) and then put them into a dataframe.

Next, I visualize the relationship between factor loadings and three items.

4. Creating index variables

We are also interested to see how scores for these factors vary across racial groups. For example, it is curious to know whether the level of marginality varies across racial groups depending on which measure we use. I created index variables by calculating the mean of survey items related to each factor. Please, note that I dropped the name_mispronounced variable in doing this, as its factor loading is quite low.

5. Replacing the survey questions with the new columns

I then replaced the survey questions related to racial experience with the new variables that represent three factors.
